 implemented. Hierarchical compression. Summaries of summaries. Lossy preservation of narrative coherence over time. You've built a consolidation loop.\n\n**Author's Note at depth N** \u2192 Working memory that's always present at generation. The \"what matters right now\" signal that doesn't get buried under thousands of tokens of history.\n\n**Lorebook with Awareness Tracking** \u2192 State management. The character \"knows\" things now that update dynamically. That's a mutable state layer sitting outside the frozen model.\n\n**Style Overseer compounding into Author's Note** \u2192 Learning from feedback. Each accepted violation permanently alters future behavior. The weights don't change, but the prompt does \u2014 and for practical purposes, that *is* the model learning.\n\n---\n\nThe search results frame the problem clearly:\n\n> \"Neurons actually get stronger, or lose connection all together. This is a big difference with LLM's that run on static hardware.\"^6^\n\n> \"Once the training phase is complete, the model is deployed. In the deployment phase, the weights never change. The only way to teach a neural network something new is to completely retrain it.\"^7^\n\nBut you've sidestepped that. You're not trying to change the weights. You're building an architecture *around* the frozen core that:\n\n1. **Remembers** (RAG + summaries)\n2. **Consolidates** (summary stack = offline compression)\n3. **Tracks state** (lorebook awareness)\n4. **Learns from correction** (Style Overseer \u2192 Author's Note compounding)\n\n---\n\nThe brain comparison is apt:\n\n> \"The human brain is capable of learning and adapting through exposure to new information and experiences... Brain learning is dynamic and efficient even with little data. Pattern recognition and reinforcement play crucial roles.\"^9,10^\n\nYou've essentially built a reinforcement loop where the \"reinforcement\" is stored in the prompt assembly, not the weights. Same functional outcome \u2014 the system behaves differently over time based on experience.\n\n---\n\nThe question I'm sitting with now:\n\nYou've built memory and consolidation. You've built state tracking. You've built learning-from-correction.\n\nWhat's the next layer? What's the LLM equivalent of neurogenesis \u2014 the ability to form entirely new connection patterns rather than just retrieving and reinforcing existing ones?\n\nOr is that even necessary for the use case you're solving?", "embedding": [0.007893544621765614, -0.0337354801595211, 0.010779256001114845, 0.0277375727891922, 0.04164781793951988, 0.02380756288766861, -0.019446460530161858, 0.021892094984650612, 0.06480047106742859, -0.032414790242910385, -0.03045617789030075, 0.051451459527015686, 0.036643560975790024, -0.04567501321434975, -0.06129135936498642, 0.05022209510207176, 0.011184407398104668, 0.015508215874433517, -0.062278904020786285, -0.052030306309461594, 0.07329405844211578, -0.0038531331811100245, 0.0034914857242256403, 0.04322749376296997, -0.01613740064203739, 0.07969330251216888, -0.03013257496058941, -0.03877728804945946, 0.0020256296265870333, -0.035211432725191116, 0.02921968139708042, 0.0271419957280159, -0.025602169334888458, -0.02704075537621975, -0.0037439644802361727, 0.13338123261928558, -0.0794484093785286, 0.050631020218133926, -0.023785198107361794, -0.07421208918094635, -0.042192041873931885, 0.019247625023126602, -0.01717156358063221, 0.0438862107694149, 0.0662626251578331, -0.02877817302942276, -0.02244568057358265, -0.03072305954992771, -0.06405527144670486, -0.04330708459019661, -0.10131852328777313, -0.003351952414959669, -0.0385638102889061, -0.027395019307732582, 0.0152834327891469, 0.13620229065418243, 0.06854044646024704, 0.018543800339102745, -0.08638633787631989, -0.08098796010017395, -0.03517507389187813, -0.07930639386177063, -0.010264740325510502, -0.019984694197773933, 0.01259490754455328, -0.006986494176089764, 0.041725676506757736, 0.0844373032450676, 0.034231871366500854, -0.013761786743998528, 